%S A395027 5,14,21,31,85,152,40,40,195,195,528,363,465,637,465,511,661,1108,637,
%T A395027 637,1721,830,2826,2265,807,1157,2005,1268,5465,3791,3488,3709,2896,
%U A395027 3986,5555,8692,7647,3442,3715,3912,2709,2147,6146,4154,3760,7421,7421,4549,11985,3675
%N A395027 The exponent k of the first pair of powers of 2 (2^j, 2^k), j < k, where 2^k is the smallest power whose last n digits are a non-identical anagram (besides n=1), no leading zeros, of the last n digits of 2^j.
%C A395027 If a(n) < 4*5^(n-1) then the non-identical condition does not change terms. - _David A. Corneth_, May 29 2026
%H A395027 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A395027/b395027.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a> (terms 501..800 from David A. Corneth)
%H A395027 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A395027/a395027.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%e A395027 For a(1), k = 5, j = 1 since the last digit of 2^5 = 32 and 2^1 = 2 are the same.
%e A395027 For a(2), k = 14, j = 11 since the last two digits of 2^14 = 16384 and 2^11 = 2048 are distinct anagrams.
%e A395027 a(3) = 21 as 21 is the smallest k whose last 3 digits (152) are an anagram of the last 3 digits of 2^j (j = 9 with anagram 512) and both anagrams have no leading zeros. - _David A. Corneth_, May 28 2026
%e A395027 For a(5), k = 85, j = 56 since the last five digits of 2^85 = 3...97632 and 2^56 = 7...27936 are anagrams. (If leading zeros were allowed, we would have k = 71 and j = 26 from 2^71 = 2...06848 and 2^26 = 6...08864.)
%o A395027 (Python)
%o A395027 def a(n):
%o A395027     if n == 1: return 5
%o A395027     seen, modder = dict(), 10**n
%o A395027     pow2mod = pow(2, 3*n, modder)
%o A395027     for k in range(3*n, modder+1):
%o A395027         s = str(pow2mod)
%o A395027         if len(s) == n:
%o A395027             key = "".join(sorted(s))
%o A395027             if key in seen and seen[key][0] != s:
%o A395027                 return k
%o A395027             else:
%o A395027                 seen[key] = (s, k)
%o A395027         pow2mod = 2*pow2mod%modder
%o A395027     return -1
%o A395027 print([a(n) for n in range(1, 51)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, May 28 2026
